definition.value: Any chlorophenol derivative that contains three covalently bonded chlorine atoms.
A purine nucleobase found in humans and other organisms.
A poly(glycerol phosphate) having an alanyl group attached to the hydroxy function of the repeating unit.
A glucosiduronic acid resulting from the formal condensation of any substance with beta-D-glucuronic acid to form a glycosidic bond.
The aldehyde formed from acetic acid by reduction of the carboxy group. It is the most abundant carcinogen in tobacco smoke.
A 3-oxo monocarboxylic acid that is butyric acid bearing a 3-oxo substituent.
A thiol comprising a panthothenate unit in phosphoric anhydride linkage with a 3',5'-adenosine diphosphate unit; and an aminoethanethiol unit.
A methyl ketone that consists of propane bearing an oxo group at C2.
A choline that is the parent compound of the cholines class, consisting of ethanolamine having three methyl substituents attached to the amino function.
A sulfur-containing amino acid that is propanoic acid with an amino group at position 2 and a sulfanyl group at position 3.
A dicarboxylic acid dianion obtained by the deprotonation of both the carboxy groups of acetylenedicarboxylic acid.
A 2-oxo monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of pyruvic acid, arising from deprotonation of the carboxy group.
An acetylenic fatty acid anion and the conjugate base of propynoic acid, arising from deprotonation of the carboxylic acid group.
A simple monocarboxylic acid containing two carbons.
A large group of antibiotics isolated from various species of Streptomyces and characterised by having a substituted phenoxazine ring linked to two cyclic heterodetic peptides.
An oxygen hydride consisting of an oxygen atom that is covalently bonded to two hydrogen atoms.

The general name for the hydrogen nucleus, to be used without regard to the hydrogen nuclear mass (either for hydrogen in its natural abundance or where it is not desired to distinguish between the isotopes).
An adenosine 5'-phosphate in which the 5'-phosphate is a triphosphate group. It is involved in the transportation of chemical energy during metabolic pathways.
The simplest (and the only achiral) proteinogenic amino acid, with a hydrogen atom as its side chain.
A xylan compound with beta-(1->4)-linkages between each xylose.
An adenosine 5'-phosphate that is coenzyme A in which the phosphate group at position 3' has been replaced by a hydrogen atom. It is an intermediate metabolite in pantothenate and CoA biosynthesis
The D-enantiomer of alanine.
An optically active form of malate having (R)-configuration.
An optically active form of malate having (S)-configuration.
A C4-dicarboxylate resulting from deprotonation of both carboxy groups of malic acid.
The L-enantiomer of leucine.
A N-alkylglycine that is the N-methyl derivative of glycine. It is an intermediate in the metabolic pathway of glycine.
The (3Z)-isomer of (2R)-phycocyanobilin.
The (3Z)-isomer of phytochromobilin.
A leukotriene that is (7E,9E,11Z,14Z)-icosa-7,9,11,14-tetraenoic acid substituted by a hydroxy group at position 5 (5S) and an L-cystein-S-yl group at position 6 (6R).

A member of the class of acrylamides that is acrylamide which is substituted at positions 2 and 3 by 2-furyl and 5-nitro-2-furyl groups, respectively (the trans isomer). Formerly used as a food preservative, it was withdrawn from the market following suspicions of carcenogenicity.
The D-enantiomer of tartaric acid.
A 2,3-dihydroxybutanedioic acid that has meso configuration.
A tetraric acid that is butanedioic acid substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 2 and 3.
An imidazolidine-2,4-dione that is 5-aminohydantoin in which a carbamoyl group is attached to the exocyclic nitrogen.
An optically active form of allantoin having (R)-(-)-configuration.
An optically active form of allantoin having (S)-(+)-configuration.
A methyl ketone that is butan-2-one substituted by a hydroxy group at position 3.
